</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-44_ pf-text-1"><strong>Developmental considerations</strong> - The anatomical structure of young children, especially infants (e.g., smaller airways and underdeveloped lungs), means that even a small obstruction or delay can quickly lead to severe hypoxia or cardiac arrest.





































</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-46_ pf-text-1"><strong>Common risks </strong>- Children and babies are at a higher risk for choking and drowning, incidents where rescue breaths are often critical for survival.






































</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-48_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-49_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-50_ pf-heading-1-h3">Legislation and best practices
